[[File:Lionel Barrymore 2.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|Barrymore in the 1910s]] [[Lionel Barrymore]] (born Lionel Herbert Blythe; 1878–1954) was an American actor of stage, screen and radio. He also directed several films, wrote scripts, created etchings, sketches and composed music.<ref name="ANBO: LB" /> He was the eldest child of the actors [[Maurice Barrymore]] and [[Georgiana Drew|Georgie Drew Barrymore]], and his two siblings were [[John Barrymore|John]] and [[Ethel Barrymore|Ethel]]; these and other family members were part of an [[Barrymore family|acting dynasty]].<ref name="ANBO: JB" />{{sfn|Byers|1998|pp=28–30}} Reluctant to follow his parents' career,{{sfn|Barrymore|1951|p=40}} Barrymore appeared together with his grandmother [[Louisa Lane Drew]] in a stage production of ''[[The Rivals]]'' at the age of 15.{{sfn|Byers|1998|p=29}} He soon found success on stage in character roles. Although he took a break from acting in 1906–09 to train in Paris as a painter, he was not successful as an artist and returned to the US and acting.<ref name="ANBO: LB" /> He also joined his family troupe, from 1910, in their [[vaudeville]] act.{{sfn|Cullen|2004|p=72}}
Barrymore began his film career in 1911, appearing in numerous [[silent film]]s, many of which have subsequently been [[lost film|lost]]. In 1912 he signed a contract with [[D. W. Griffith]]'s [[Biograph Company]] and appeared as a character actor in short films before moving into feature-length productions in 1914.<ref name="ANBO: LB" /> He began writing scripts and directing films shortly afterwards, and for the next five years he did not act on the legitimate stage.{{sfn|Peters|1990|p=533}} Although he had several successes on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] after the First World War, he encountered strongly negative criticism in a 1921 production of ''[[Macbeth]]'' and in three productions in a row in 1925. Afterwards, he never again appeared on the New York stage.<ref name="ANBO: LB" /> In 1925 he signed a contract with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], where he became a close friend of [[Louis B. Mayer]] and for whom he made numerous films.<ref name="ANBO: LB" /> He directed several films from 1929 to 1931 but concentrated on acting after that.<ref name="AFI: Filmography" /><ref name="BFI: Filmography" />
Barrymore became well known in curmudgeonly roles.<ref name="EB: LB" /> In 1938 he broke his hip and, aggravated by arthritis, he lived the remainder of his life in a wheelchair.{{sfn|Kotsilibas-Davis|1981|pp=215–16}} Mayer made sure that roles were found or written to accommodate Barrymore, who continued to act in films until 1953.<ref name="ANBO: LB" />{{sfn|Kotsilibas-Davis|1981|p=217}} During that time he appeared as Dr. Gillespie in the popular Dr. Kildare film series with [[Lew Ayres]] in the titular role,{{sfn|Kotsilibas-Davis|1981|pp=222–24}} and as [[Mr. Potter]] in ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]''—a role that was highly placed on the [[American Film Institute]]'s list of the [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Heroes & Villains|100 Heroes and Villains]]<ref name="AFI 100" /> in a film that the critic [[Philip French]] described as "a complex inspirational work".<ref name="French: IAWW" /> Beginning in the 1930s, Barrymore increasingly worked in radio, initially as [[Ebenezer Scrooge]] in [[Charles Dickens]]'s ''[[Adaptations of A Christmas Carol#Radio|A Christmas Carol]]'', which was broadcast annually from 1934 to 1953,{{sfn|Dunning|1998|p=153}} then in ''[[Mayor of the Town (radio program)|Mayor of the Town]]'' beginning in 1942,{{sfn|Terrace|1998|pp=221–222}} and also in a radio series spun off from the Dr. Kildare films (playing the same character that he had played in the films), among others.{{sfn|Kotsilibas-Davis|1981|p=223}}
Two of the films in which Barrymore appeared—''[[Grand Hotel (1932 film)|Grand Hotel]]'' (1932) and ''[[You Can't Take It with You (film)|You Can't Take It with You]]'' (1938)—won the [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]].<ref name="AMPAS: Grand Hotel" /><ref name="AMPAS: Take it" /> He was considered for the [[Academy Award for Best Director]] for his 1929 film, ''[[Madame X (1929 film)|Madame X]]'',{{efn|The "consideration" in the early ceremonies is not classed by the [[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] as an official nomination. The Academy states that "Though not official nominations, the additional names in each category, according to in-house records, were under consideration by the various boards of judges."<ref name="AMPAS: Madame X" />}} and won the [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] award for his performance in ''[[A Free Soul]]'' (1931). He was inducted to the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] on February 8, 1960<ref name="WoF: Barrymore" /> and is, along with his two siblings, included in the [[American Theater Hall of Fame]].<ref name="Hall o F" />
